data.content:
Your test works but `Assert.IsTrue` gives poor failure messages. MSTest 3.x+ has specialized collection assertions with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
}
```

**Key changes:**

| Before (`Assert.IsTrue`) | After (specialized) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | Failure says "collection was empty" vs generic "expected True" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | Failure shows actual count |
| `Single()` + `Assert.IsTrue(x != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Clearer failure; returns the element if needed |

The `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(...))` is fine — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" method, so `IsTrue` is appropriate there.
